@node The Design of FSet
@chapter The Design of FSet

The purpose of this chapter is to explain the major design decisions that went into FSet.  It's
probably of greatest interest to experienced Common Lisp programmers who want to use the library,
and to other language/library designers.

My design desiderata for FSet were, in roughly decreasing order of importance:

@itemize
@item
Elegant set-theoretic semantics

@item
Good integration with Common Lisp

@item
An API that is general, easy to use, and reasonably complete

@item
Good time performance, in both a time-complexity sense and a constant-factor sense

@item
Space overhead is reasonably small
@end itemize

Don't be daunted by the term ``set-theoretic''.  All I mean by it is that FSet collections are
nestable: you can have sets of sets, maps keyed by seqs (FSet's sequences) or even sets of seqs,
@i{etc. etc.}, with no additional effort on your part.  While such types aren't often needed in
application programming, they do show up sometimes in compiler work.

The latter two properties drove the choice of data structures; see @ref{FSet Data Structures}.  The
first three more concern the API.  In particular, the first two are somewhat in conflict, as I'll
now explain.

@c I feel this needs more intro/overview material before just diving into the divergences.

@c Map defaults should be mentioned here somewhere; they also support DRY.

@hrule{}


@c ================================================================================
@node Divergences from Common Lisp
@section Divergences from Common Lisp
There are two major ways in which FSet's collections differ from the ones built into CL.

@c Rewrite in light of earlier discussion
The first, of course, is the functional semantics.  This isn't a total departure, because lists are
frequently used functionally.  But, of course, cons cells sometimes are used as mutable objects;
arrays are usually used as mutable objects; the CL sequence functions, that abstract over lists and
vectors, expect mutability; and hash tables are mutable objects.

In @ref{What Is a Functional Datatype?}, I explained what a functional datatype is, and pointed out
that they can provide operations that can be conceptualized either as computing a new value for a
collection and reassigning it to the variable holding it, or as a mutation to an unaliasable value.

This means that FSet's update operations have to work differently from most CL builtins.  The
clearest example has to do with the behavior of @code{setf}.  (I'll say more about @code{setf}
@href{Quasi-Mutating Operators, below}; non-CL-programmers might want to read that first.)  If you
have a CL vector @code{v}, you can set one of its elements using @code{setf} of @code{elt}:

@example
(setf (elt v i) x)
@end example

If, instead, you have an FSet seq @code{s}, you can write an expression that looks superficially similar:

@example
(setf (lookup s i) x)
@end example

However, it means something quite different.  In the @code{elt} case, if there are other variables
directly or indirectly bound to @code{v}, they will also see the change: a mutable shared object has been
modified.  The @code{lookup} case, however, is equivalent to

@example
  (setq s (with s i x))
@end example

where the FSet @code{with} operation returns an updated seq that now has @code{x} at index @code{i}.
The change will not be visible anywhere except through variable @code{s}.

I have occasionally heard people complain that this is against the spirit of the language, but it
really isn't.  Consider this example:

@example
  (let* ((a nil)
         (b a))
    (push 'foo a)
    b)
@end example

Every CL programmer knows, without even thinking about it, that the above evaluates to @code{nil}: the
modification performed by @code{push} is visible only through @code{a}, not through @code{b}.  Lists are usually
used functionally, and this, notwithstanding the @code{setq} implied by the @code{push}, is an example; there
is no potentially shared list object being modified here.

"But," some might say, "that's @code{push}, not @code{setf}." All right, here's another example:

@example
  (let* ((a 1)
         (b a))
    (setf (ldb (byte 2 1) a) 3)   ; a becomes 7
    b)
@end example

Here there's a @code{setf} of an expression wrapping @code{a}, but its effect is still just to assign a new
value to @code{a}; @code{b} is still 1.  Again, every CL programmer knows this without thinking about it;
integers are not aliasing, mutable objects.

So no matter how long you've been writing Common Lisp, learning FSet is not going to break your
brain.

The second major way in which FSet's design diverges somewhat from CL's has to do with semantic
loading.  Lisp lists are semantically @emph{unloaded}.  A list can be used as a sequence; as a set,
where order is unimportant and duplicates are not allowed; as a bag, where order is unimportant and
duplicates @emph{are} allowed; as a map, in either alist or plist form; or in many other ways.  So,
as a programmer writing code to do something with a list, you have to remember the intended
semantics of this particular list.  Also, you have to remember what equivalence relation you
intended to compare elements with.  Sometimes, the default of @code{eql} suffices, but often, you
want to compare elements by their contents rather than their identity; in such cases, you have to
pass in the equivalence relation every time you call @code{member}, @code{assoc}, @code{find},
@i{etc.}  But doing so violates the well-known ``DRY principle'' (Don't Repeat Yourself).

In contrast, FSet collections are semantically @emph{loaded}: they carry their semantics, including the
applicable equivalence relation, along with them, so you don't have to supply it at every call.  (CL
hash tables are like this too, so again, it's not a complete departure.)

This semantic loading makes code that uses FSet more elegant, and practically eliminates bugs that
can occur when a list is not used consistently across the program.  But it did cause one design
quandary.  I wanted to provide shadowed versions of Lisp builtins like @code{find}, @code{position},
@code{count}, @i{etc.} that would work on FSet collections but would bounce to the CL builtins if
passed a list.  The catch was, FSet has its own default notion of equality; defaulting to @code{eql}
didn't make sense.

I finally settled on this approach: While generic versions of a number of operations will be
provided, it is critical for the user to understand that the purpose of this genericity is
@strong{@emph{not}} so that you can write code that will actually be called on both Lisp sequences
and the FSet types.  Rather, the goal is more modest: to make familiar functionality accessible by
familiar names, so that you can write FSet code without having to learn new names for @code{find}
@i{etc.}

One issue with this approach has to do with the Lisp names @code{first}, @code{rest}, @code{last},
and @code{second} through @code{seventh}.  First, let's note the inconsistencies already in CL:

@itemize
@item
These are not generic sequence operations, but work only on lists.

@item
@code{last} doesn't return the last element of a list, but rather the last @emph{cons} in the list.

@end itemize

For FSet @dfn{seqs} --- as the sequence type is called, to distinguish it from CL sequences --- I
felt it was important to treat @code{first} and @code{last} symmetrically, since the implementation
is symmetric.  Also, there is a whole structure of related operations operating on the ends of seqs;
I have called these @code{with-first}, @code{with-last}, @code{less-first}, @code{less-last},
@code{push-first}, @code{push-last}, @code{pop-first}, and @code{pop-last}, the first four being the
functional update operations, and the last four being the modify macros that invoke the first four,
respectively.  Because of the importance of these operations, I felt it would be acceptable to force
some compromises on existing code.  So FSet exports a generic function @code{first} which includes a
compatibility method for lists; here the impact on existing code is limited to the cost of the CLOS
dispatch.  For @code{last}, however, I decided to make an @strong{incompatible} change:
@code{fset2:last}, on a list, returns the last element rather than the last cons.  FSet also exports
the functionality of @code{cl:last} as @code{lastcons} --- clearly a better name.

FSet does not, however, export any version of @code{rest}, or of @code{second} through
@code{seventh}.  For @code{rest}, I think @code{less-first} is better because it participates in the
symmetric structure shown above.

@anchor{@code{head} and @code{tail}}
(From the perspective of FSet, with its symmetric functional sequences, it strikes me as a little
unfortunate that the names that caught on as modern replacements for @code{car} and @code{cdr} were
@code{first} and @code{rest} instead of, say, @code{head} and @code{tail}.  @code{first} and
@code{rest}, it seems to me, are naturally applied to any sequence, where @code{head} and
@code{tail} more specifically suggest the structure of a list.  So FSet exports @code{head} and
@code{tail} as synonyms for @code{car} and @code{cdr}.)

Another issue: I mentioned above that generic-function versions of @code{find-if} @i{etc.} are
provided.  They are, but they are not completely compatible when invoked on FSet types (they
@emph{are} completely compatible when invoked on Lisp sequences).  The primary differences are:

@itemize
@item
The default for @code{:test} is @code{#'fset:equal?} rather than @code{#'eql}.  Yes, it's a little weird to key
this off of the collection class.  But remember, our purpose is not true genericity, but merely
mental convenience.  In that light, if you're invoking one of these on an FSet collection, it's
fair to conclude that you're working within an FSet context, and FSet semantics should apply.

@item
The @code{:test-not} keyword is not supported (it's deprecated in the ANSI spec).
@end itemize


