@node The @code{@@} Macro
@section The @code{@@} Macro

@c &&& Rather think I should also have a defmac for this in the API reference, to which at least
@c some of the current refs should point (though it should in turn point here).

Common Lisp is a "Lisp-2", meaning a two-namespace Lisp in which a given name can have both a
function binding and a value binding.  In a Lisp-1, like Scheme, it would be nice to set the FSet
types up as objects that could be called as functions as well as having the various operations
invoked on them (some object systems for other Lisps have supported this, such as that of
@uref{http://mumble.net/~jar/tproject/,T}).  Then, instead of @code{(lookup m x)} where @code{m} is
a map, you could write simply @code{(m x)}.  But this doesn't work in a Lisp-2, since the @code{car}
of a form is evaluated in the function namespace; you'd have to write @code{(funcall m x)}, which
isn't any more elegant.

What I can do, however, is give you a shorter name to type than @code{funcall}.  Thus is born
@code{@@}.  It is a macro that expands to code that tests whether its first argument is a Lisp
function; if so, it funcalls it (with the supplied arguments); otherwise it calls @code{lookup} on
it.  So you can use it when writing higher-order code to make it accept a map as well as a unary
Lisp function.  (Also, a seq behaves as a map from index to element, and a set behaves as a map from
value to boolean, and a bag behaves as a map from value to multiplicity.)

Whether you want to use @code{@@} generally, in place of @code{lookup}, is a matter of taste.  Both
are @code{setf}-able; though doing @code{(setf (@@ m x) y)} works only if @code{m} is an FSet
collection.  Remember, this doesn't modify the collection; it's equivalent to @code{(setf m (with m
x y))}.

@cindex Emacs
If you use Emacs for editing, you might find that it doesn't treat @code{@@} as a symbol, which can
occasionally be annoying.  Adding this line to your init file (@code{~/.emacs} or
@code{~/.emacs.d/init.el}) should cure the problem:

@example
(modify-syntax-entry ?@ "_" lisp-mode-syntax-table)
@end example


